Convert specs to RSpec 2.14.8 syntax with Transpec

This conversion is done by Transpec 1.13.1 with the following command:
    transpec

* 24 conversions
    from: obj.should
      to: expect(obj).to

* 10 conversions
    from: its(:attr) { }
      to: describe '#attr' do subject { super().attr }; it { } end

* 9 conversions
    from: == expected
      to: eq(expected)

* 4 conversions
    from: collection.should have(n).items
      to: expect(collection.size).to eq(n)

Merge pull request #44 from rroblak/fix_error_status_10

Fix bug that skips notification on error status 10

Fix bug that skips notification on error status 10

The current behavior incorrectly skips a notification when an error
status code of 10 is received from Apple. Consider a scenario where the
notifications array looks like:

notifications = [notification_a, notification_b, notification_c]

Let's say that after writing notification_a, Apple responds with an
error-response packet that has a status code of 10 and an Identifier of
0, indicating that notification_a was the last (and only) notification
successfully sent.

With the current logic, index would be set to 0 and then bumped to 1.
The slice! on notifications would then modify notifications so that its
value is just [notification_c]. So notification_a would've been
successfully sent, notification_c would be queued up for sending, but
notification_b would be dropped and never sent.

Getting rid of the increment to index fixes this bug, so that both
notification_b and notification_c will be queued up for resending.

Merge branch 'notification-format-2' of github.com:drodriguez/houston into drodriguez-notification-format-2

Conflicts:
	lib/houston.rb

Handle correctly the shutdown status

According to Apple docs the shutdown status reports back the last
notification identifier successfully sent, so advance the index once to
not send a notification twice.

Implement and spec new notification format "2"

Apple modified the Local and Push Notification Programming Guide last
April specifying a new format “2” and labeling simple and enhanced
formats as legacy.

New priority attribute. According to Apple it could be 10 or 5 (or
nothing?). Those values are not enforced, in case other values appear.

Expiration and identifier are no longer neccessary. The identifier is
added by the Houston::Client.

Using ‘n’ and ‘N‘ for packs and unpacks, since Apple documents that all
data is network order (big endian), and ‘i’ is native endianess.

Prepare for Rspec.

Need to split into lib/houston.rb and lib/houston/version.rb, otherwise
the gemspec require was loading the gem before simplecov could kick in,
and it didn’t report any coverage.
